---
// Static discussion-prompt grid for festival programmers, educators,
// policy researchers. Designed to print to a single page.
---
<div class="panel p-6 md:p-10">
  <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-gold-400">Discussion Kit</p>
  <h3 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl text-white">
    Prompts for festival panels, classrooms, and policy roundtables.
  </h3>
  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-white/60 max-w-2xl">
    Eight prompts grounded in the corpus. Use them after a screening, before a
    Q&amp;A, or in a media-studies seminar. Each prompt has a built-in path
    back to the data — so the conversation has somewhere to land.
  </p>

  <div class="mt-8 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-bolly">For programmers</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        If your slate this year were re-cut by archetype, who would feel the most pride?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        A norm audit asks not "did we book good films" but "whose interior life
        did we show on the screen the most?"
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-holly">For educators</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        Why does shame in Hollywood lean toward "I should have done better,"
        while in Bollywood it leans toward "What will people say"?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        A starting point for the individualism vs. collectivism conversation —
        with the receipts.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">For researchers</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        Hollywood female pride climbed 23 → 31% post-2015. Bollywood fell 28 → 19%.
        What policy, market, or production conditions explain the divergence?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        Worth comparing to Bechdel-2.0 work, GD-IQ, and USC Annenberg's annual reports.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-bolly">For audiences</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        Pick a scene where a character feels shame. Who decided it was shameful?
        Who benefits from that decision?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        Norms only work if they're invisible. Naming them is the first move.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-holly">For diplomats</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        Cinema is soft power. What does Hollywood's recent pride profile —
        identity, ambition, financial success — export about American norms?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        And what would Bollywood's recent pride profile export, if it traveled
        as widely?
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400">For policy researchers</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        Sexual Harassment, Modesty, Promiscuity — Bollywood-leaning, but
        present in both. What's the legal apparatus around each in the
        producing country?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        The screen lags, leads, or mirrors the law. Each is a different policy implication.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-bolly">For platforms</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        Whose pride is your recommendation engine optimizing for?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        If 79% of Bollywood pride is male, an "if you liked X" graph compounds
        that asymmetry across millions of impressions.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl bg-ink-950/40 ring-1 ring-white/5 p-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-holly">For funders</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-base text-white leading-snug">
        What's the smallest piece of cross-cultural film research that, if
        funded, would let producers measure what they're already optimizing for?
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-white/55">
        MAPGEN at corpus scale is one answer. There are others.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
